\begin_layout Standard
Physical motion can be defined simply as the change in position of an object,
 over time.
 Visual motion is more challenging to define.
 I presume that it is advantageous for perceptions of visual motion to be
 veridical, that is, to correspond to the changing positions of objects.
 However, the most well-understood mechanisms of visual motion seem to have
 little to do with explicitly tracking changes in position.
 First-order motion mechanisms are instead understood as signaling spatiotempora
l correlations of luminance within limited, stationary windows.
 With the idea of gaining an understanding of how motion as represented
 in the visual system can correspond to objects moving in physical space,
 I constructed stimuli that combining the motion of a carrier wave producing
 first-order motion, with the motion of an envelope that changed position
 over time.
 Arranging these elements in multiples, as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "mov:demo"

\end_inset

, produced the novel effect that the apearance of motion favors its first-order
 or position-defined components as a function of the spacing between elements.
 Investigating how the parameters of these stimuli affected the appearance
 of visual motion led to a model of how first-order and position-defined
 motion contribute to the appearance of visual motion.
 These experiments revealed complementary effects: first-order motion exhibits
 summation over large areas, gaining sensitivity with added signal, while
 position-defined motion exhibits spatial interference, losing sensitivity
 when flankers are introduced.
 The two signals are combined with a subtractive interaction, which may
 explain how moving objects can be dissociated from the background.
 
\end_layout

