\begin_layout Standard
This revealed that in fact most observers do show repulsion from carrier
 motion, at weak carrier motion and larger spacings; using a weak counterclockwi
se envelope motion biased most observers' responses clockwise.
 I incorporated this into the model as a repulsion parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{I}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The strength of the repulsion effect and its nonlinearity did not appear
 to vary with the number of elements; the same magnitude of repulsion appeared
 to apply to stimuli with two elements as with 4 or 6.
 As a result, at smaller spacings, repulsion is overwhelmed by global summation
 of carrier motion.
 It was also necessary to add a nonlinear term, since larger clockwise carrier
 strengths turned the apparent motion clockwise (and this was not accounted
 for by the global summation of carrier motion described earlier.) Repulsion
 depends on the strength of carrier motion, nonlinearly: an increment of
 carrier motion strength applied to pure counterphase flicker led to a decrement
 in response rate (i.e.
 observers' responses tended away from the direction of the increment added
 to carrier motion), while the same increment added to stronger motion produced
 an increment in response rate (over and above that was accounted for by
 global motion summation.) In the model, this nonlinearity leads to a nonmonotoni
c function of carrier strength; at weak carrier strengths there is repulsion,
 but at stronger carrier strengths repulsion ceased and reversed.
 This does not necessarily determine whether the actual mechanism is nonmonotoni
c, as the values that are fit in this model depend strongly on what residuals
 are left when global summation is implemented.
 The model fit is effectively separating the response due to carrier motion
 into a component that depends on element number (global summation) and
 a component that does not, which might not reflect the mechanisms involved.
 The mechanism responsible for repulsion may be saturating rather than nonmonoto
nic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The repulsion effect may be related to some of the phenomena known as induced
 motion, or the Duncker illusion (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Duncker:1938aa,Reinhardt-Rutland:1988aa"

\end_inset

, review), in which conflict between two component motions leads to an incorrect
 attribution of motion to each component.
 A familiar example of induced motion occurs when the moon is visible between
 low-lying clouds.
 When the clouds move with the wind, it gives rise to an illusion of the
 moon appearing to move in the opposite direction, while the clouds appear
 to be stationary.
 The general pattern is that induced motion arises when there is a difference
 between the motion of a larger field (the clouds in this case) and that
 of a smaller object (the moon.) The tendency is to view the field as stationary
 and attribute the difference in motion to the object; of the physical situation
 this results in a perception of object motion opposite the actual field
 motion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In my stimuli there is not a large field moving distinctly from a small
 object, but a set of identical objects with identical motion.
 But as discussed above, the spatial scale for integration of first-order
 motion appears to be larger than that for position-defined motion, and
 there is by design a conflict between the two.
 So the ingredients for a conflict between field motion and object motion
 are present, depending on which motion systems contribute to each.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some properties that have been seen for induced motion are similar to what
 I found for repulsion: there is considerable intersubject variability in
 the strength of the illusion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Murakami:1993vn,Zivotofsky:2004aa"

\end_inset

, the strength of the illusion is a nonmonotonic function of the motion
 strength and/or target contrast 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Murakami:1993vn,Serrano-Pedraza:2010aa"

\end_inset

.
 Induced motion is often explained in terms of antagonism between center
